splaystyle\mbox{and}\quad M_{j} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\sup\{f(x)\>:\>a_{j-1}\leq x\leq a_{j}\}. Note that these numbers exist, since f is bounded. The lower Riemann sum of f with respect to \mathscr{D} is l_{\mathscr{D}}(f)=\sum_{j=1}^{n}m_{j}(a_{j}-a_{j-1}), and the upper Riemann sum of f with respect to \mathscr{D} is u_{\mathscr{D}}(f)=\sum_{j=1}^{n}M_{j}(a_{j}-a_{j-1}). The idea is that a dissection of size n divides [a,b] into n subintervals, [a_{j-1},a_{j}] for j=1,2,\ldots,n . If f(x)\geq 0 for all x , then the lower Riemann sum can be visualized as the total area of the tallest rectangles with bases [a_{j-1},a_{j}] which fit under the graph y=f(x) between x=a and x=b . So l_{\mathscr{D}}(f) is an underestimate of the area under the graph. Similarly, the upper Riemann sum can be visualized as the total area of the shortest rectangles with bases [a_{j-1},a_{j}] which the graph y=f(x) between x=a and x=b fits under and is thus an overestimate of the area under the graph. This is illustrated in Figure 9. Refer to caption Refer to caption Figure 9: Lower and upper Riemann sums of a function with respect to a dissection of size 4 . Note that m_{j}\leq M_{j} for all j\in\{1,2,\ldots,n\} , so it follows immediately that, for all bounded functions f:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} and all dissections \mathscr{D} of [a,b] , l_{\mathscr{D}}(f)\leq u_{\mathscr{D}}(f). Example 12.3 \mathscr{D}_{1}=\{0,1\} , \mathscr{D}_{2}=\{0, rac{1}{2},1\} , and \mathscr{D}_{3}=\{0, rac{1}{2}, rac{3}{4},1\} are dissections of [0,1] . The function f:[0,1]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , f(x)=x^{2} is bounded, and its lower and upper Riemann sums with respect to these dissections are: \displaystyle l_{\mathscr{D}_{1}}(f) \displaystyle= \displaystyle 0(1-0)=0 \displaystyle u_{\mathscr{D}_{1}}(f) \displaystyle= \displaystyle 1(1-0)=1 \displaystyle l_{\mathscr{D}_{2}}(f) \displaystyle= \displaystyle 0( rac{1}{2}-0)+ rac{1}{4}(1- rac{1}{2})= rac{1}{8} \displaystyle u_{\mathscr{D}_{2}}(f) \displays