ot\subseteq\mathscr{D}_{2} ) and nor is \mathscr{D}_{1} a refinement of \mathscr{D}_{2} (since \mathscr{D}_{2}
ot\subseteq\mathscr{D}_{1} ). •​Every dissection \mathscr{D} of [a,b] is a refinement of the trivial dissection \mathscr{D}_{0}=\{a,b\} . •​Every dissection is the unique 0 -point refinement of itself. The idea is that a refinement \mathscr{D}^{\prime} of \mathscr{D} contains all the points in \mathscr{D} and (unless \mathscr{D}^{\prime}=\mathscr{D} ) some more points too, so it splits [a,b] up into more subintervals, at least some of which are narrower. Intuitively, one expects that passing from \mathscr{D} to a refinement of \mathscr{D} can only improve, that is, increase, the underestimate l_{\mathscr{D}}(f) . Similarly, passing to a refinement of \mathscr{D} , one expects, can only reduce the overestimate u_{\mathscr{D}}(f) . This expectation turns out to be essentially correct and is fundamental. Lemma 12.5 (Refinement Lemma) Let f:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be bounded, \mathscr{D},\mathscr{D}^{\prime} be dissections of [a,b] , and \mathscr{D}^{\prime} be a refinement of \mathscr{D} . Then l_{\mathscr{D}}(f)\leq l_{\mathscr{D}^{\prime}}(f)\leq u_{\mathscr{D}^{\prime}% }(f)\leq u_{\mathscr{D}}(f). Proof. We first prove this in the special case where \mathscr{D}^{\prime} is a 1 -point refinement of \mathscr{D} . So, let \mathscr{D}=\{a=a_{0},a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}=b\} and \mathscr{D}^{\prime}=\mathscr{D}\cup\{z\} where z\in[a,b]{ ackslash}\mathscr{D} . Then there exists k\in\{1,\ldots,n\} such that z\in(a_{k-1},a_{k}) . Let \displaystyle m_{j} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\inf\{f(x)\>:\>a_{j}\leq x\leq a_{j-1}\} \displaystyle m^{\prime} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\inf\{f(x)\>:\>a_{k-1}\leq x\leq z\} \displaystyle m^{\prime\prime} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\inf\{f(x)\>:\>z\leq x\leq a_{k}\} \displaystyle M_{j} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\sup\{f(x)\>:\>a_{j}\leq x\leq a_{j-1}\} \displaystyle M^{\prime} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\sup\{f(x)\>:\>a_{k-1}\leq x\leq z\} \displaystyle M^{\prime\prime} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\sup\{f(x)\>:\>z\leq x\leq a_{k}\} and no