ma^{\prime}}. So this notation forces you to focus on something irrevelevant (the name of the symbol x ) instead of thinking about what the function f really is. Incidentally, do we know that the integral (12.17) exists? The next section will answer this question with a resounding “yes!” 12.3 Continuous functions are integrable We have seen that all differentiable functions are continuous (Theorem 9.8), but not all continuous functions are differentiable. We next prove that every continuous function (on a closed bounded interval) is Riemann integrable. Once again, the converse is false: we’ve already seen an example of an integrable function that is not continuous (the step function Example 12.9). Theorem 12.13 Let f:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be continuous. Then f is Riemann integrable. Proof. First note that, since f is continuous, it is certainly bounded (by the Extreme Value Theorem), so l_{\mathscr{D}}(f) and u_{\mathscr{D}}(f) exist for any dissection \mathscr{D} of [a,b] . Consider the sequence (\mathscr{D}_{n}) of regular dissections of [a,b] of size 2^{n} . Then \mathscr{D}_{n}\subset\mathscr{D}_{n+1} for all n , so by the Refinement Lemma, l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) is increasing (and bounded above) and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) is decreasing (and bounded below). Hence, by the Monotone Convergence Theorem (Theorem 3.20), u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)ightarrow L,\qquad l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)ightarrow K for some L,K\in{\mathbb{R}} and, by Proposition 2.14 and Lemma 12.6, K\leq L . It remains to show that L-K=0 . Assume, towards a contradiction, that L-K>0 . For a given fixed n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} , define as usual \displaystyle m_{j} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\inf\{f(x)\>:\>a_{j-1}\leq x\leq a_{j}\} \displaystyle\mbox{and}\quad M_{j} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\sup\{f(x)\>:\>a_{j-1}\leq x\leq a_{j}\}. Then u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)-l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)= rac{b-a}{2^{n}}\sum_{j=1}^{2^{% n}}(M_{j}-m_{j})\geq L-K. This sum consists of 2^{n} terms, each non-negative, so at least one term must be greater than or equal to (L-K)/2^{n} . That is, there must exist j\in\{1,2,\ldots,2^{n}\} such that M_{j}-m_{j}\geq rac{L-K}{b-a}. But f:[a_{j-1},a_{j}]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is continuous so, by the Extreme Value Theorem, f attains both a maximum and minimum value on [a_{j-1},a_{j}] , that is, there are points, x_{n} and y_{n} say, in [a_{j-1},a_{j}] such that f(x_{n})=M_{j} and f(y_{n})=m_{j} . Hence, for each n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} there exist x_{n},y_{n}\in[a,b] such that (12.18) (12.18) \displaystyle|x_{n}-y_{n}| \displaystyle\leq \displaystyle rac{b-a}{2^{n}}, (12.19) (12.19) \displaystyle f(x_{n})-f(y_{n}) \displaystyle\geq \displaystyle rac{L-K}{b-a}. Consider the sequence (x_{n}) . It is bounded, so, by the Bolzano–Weierstrass Theorem, it has a convergent subsequence x_{n_{k}}ightarrow c\in[a,b] . By (12.18), x_{n_{k}}- rac{b-a}{2^{n_{k}}}\leq y_{n_{k}}\leq x_{n_{k}}+ rac{b-a}{2^{n_{k% }}} so y_{n_{k}}ightarrow c also, by the Squeeze Rule. Now f is continuous, so f(x_{n_{k}})ightarrow f(c) and f(y_{n_{k}})ightarrow f(c) , and hence f(x_{n_{k}})-f(y_{n_{k}})ightarrow f(c)-f(c)=0 . But this contradicts (12.19) and Proposition 2.14. ∎ The function f:[0,1]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , f(x)=\sqrt{x^{2}+1} is a composition of continuous functions, so is continuous, so we know that the integral (12.17) exists by Theorem 12.13. 12.4 Elementary properties of the Riemann integral The Riemann integral has many convenient properties. Theorem 12.14 (The Join Rule) Let f be Riemann integrable on [a,b] and on [b,c] . Then f is Riemann integrable on [a,c] and \int_{a}^{c}f=\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{b}^{c}f. Proof. By assumption, there exist sequences of dissections (\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}) of [a,b] and (\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}) of [b,c] such that l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(f)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f , u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(f)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f , l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(f)ightarrow\int_{b}^{c}f , and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(f)ightarrow\int_{b}^{c}f . Let \mathscr{D}_{n}=\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}\cup\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime} . Then \mathscr{D}_{n} is a dissection of [a,c] and it follows directly from Definition 12.2 that l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)=l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(f)+l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{% \prime\prime}}(f) and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)=u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(f)+u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{% \prime\prime}}(f) . Hence, by the Algebra of Limits, l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{b}^{c}f and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{b}^{c}f , so the claim follows. ∎ We next want to prove that the Riemann integral is linear, that is, \int_{a}^{b}(\alpha f+ eta g)=\alpha\int_{a}^{b}f+ eta\int_{a}^{b}g , for any constants \alpha, eta . To do this, we need the following: Lemma 12.15 Let f,g:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be bounded functions and \mathscr{D} be a dissection of [a,b] . Then l_{\mathscr{D}}(f+g)\geq l_{\mathscr{D}}(f)+l_{\mathscr{D}}(g)\quad\mbox{and}% \quad u_{\mathscr{D}}(f+g)\leq u_{\mathscr{D}}(f)+u_{\mathscr{D}}(g). Proof. Let \mathscr{D}=\{a_{0},a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\} and I_{j}=[a_{j-1},a_{j}] . Let \displaystyle m_{j}(f) \displaystyle= \displaystyle\inf\{f(x)\>:\>x\in I_{j}\}, \displaystyle M_{j}(f) \displaystyle= \displaystyle\sup\{f(x)\>:\>x\in I_{j}\}, and m_{j}(g),M_{j}(g),m_{j}(g+f) , and M_{j}(g+f) be defined similarly. Then, for all x\in I_{j} , f(x)+g(x)\geq m_{j}(f)+m_{j}(g) , so m_{j}(f)+m_{j}(g) is certainly a lower bound on \{f(x)+g(x)\>:\>x\in I_{j}\} . Since m_{j}(f+g) is the greatest lower bound on this set, it follows that m_{j}(f+g)\geq m_{j}(f)+m_{j}(g) . Hence \displaystyle l_{\mathscr{D}}(f+g) \displaystyle= \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{n}m_{j}(f+g)(a_{j}-a_{j-1}) \displaystyle\geq \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{n}(m_{j}(f)+m_{j}(g))(a_{j}-a_{j-1})=l_{\mathscr{D}}(% f)+l_{\mathscr{D}}(g). Similarly, for all x\in I_{j} , f(x)+g(x)\leq M_{j}(f)+M_{j}(g) , so M_{j}(f)+M_{j}(g) is certainly an upper bound on \{f(x)+g(x)\>:\>x\in I_{j}\} . Since M_{j}(f+g) is the least upper bound on this set, it follows that M_{j}(f+g)\leq M_{j}(f)+M_{j}(g) . Hence \displaystyle u_{\mathscr{D}}(f+g) \displaystyle= \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{n}M_{j}(f+g)(a_{j}-a_{j-1}) \displaystyle\leq \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{n}(M_{j}(f)+M_{j}(g))(a_{j}-a_{j-1})=u_{\mathscr{D}}(% f)+u_{\mathscr{D}}(g). ∎ Theorem 12.16 (Linearity of the Riemann Integral) Let f,g be Riemann integrable on [a,b] , and \alpha\in{\mathbb{R}} be a constant. Then (i)​ \alpha f is Riemann integrable on [a,b] , and \int_{a}^{b}\alpha f=\alpha\int_{a}^{b}f , (ii)​ f+g is Riemann integrable on [a,b] , and \int_{a}^{b}(f+g)=\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{a}^{b}g . Proof. (i) By assumption, there is a sequence of dissections (\mathscr{D}_{n}) such that l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f . It follows directly from Definition 12.2 that l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(\alpha f)=\alpha l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(\alpha f)=\alpha u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) if \alpha\geq 0 , and l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(\alpha f)=\alpha u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(\alpha f)=\alpha l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) if \alpha<0 . In either case, l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(\alpha f)ightarrow\alpha\int_{a}^{b}f and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(\alpha f)ightarrow\alpha\int_{a}^{b}f by the Algebra of Limits, and the claim follows. (ii) Let (\mathscr{D}_{n}) be as defined above. By assumption, there is also a sequence of dissections (\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}) such that l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(g)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}g and u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(g)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}g . Let \mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}=\mathscr{D}_{n}\cup\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime} , and note that this is a refinement of both \mathscr{D}_{n} and \mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime} . Now, by Lemma 12.15 and the Refinement Lemma \displaystyle l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)+l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(g)\leq l_{% \mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(f)+l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(g) \displaystyle\leq \displaystyle l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(f+g) \displaystyle\leq \displaystyle u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(f+g)\leq u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{% \prime\prime}}(f)+u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(g)\leq u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}% }(f)+u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(g). Now l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)+l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(g)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f% +\int_{a}^{b}g,\quad u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)+u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(g)% ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{a}^{b}g, by the Algebra of Limits, so u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(f+g)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{a}^{b}g,% \quad l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}(f+g)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{a}% ^{b}g by the Squeeze Rule. Hence, f+g is Riemann integrable and \int_{a}^{b}(f+g)=\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{a}^{b}g ∎ We next prove that Riemann integration preserves inequalities. Proposition 12.17 Let f,g:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be Riemann integrable and assume f(x)\leq g(x) for all x\in[a,b] . Then \int_{a}^{b}f\leq\int_{a}^{b}g. Proof. By assumption there exist sequences of dissections \mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime} , \mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime} such that l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}}(f)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f and l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime}}ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}g . Let \mathscr{D}_{n}=\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime}\cup\mathscr{D}_{n}^{\prime\prime} . Then, by the Refinement Lemma (and the Squeeze Rule) l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f)ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}f and l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}ightarrow\int_{a}^{b}g also. But, for each n , l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(g)\geq l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) since \inf g\geq\inf f on any subset of [a,b] . Hence, \int_{a}^{b}g-\int_{a}^{b}f , being the limit of a convergent non-negative sequence, is \geq 0 (Proposition 2.14). ∎ Recall that the triangle inequality asserts that, for any pair of real numbers x_{1},x_{2} , |x_{1}+x_{2}|\leq|x_{1}|+|x_{2}|. It is but the work of a moment to prove (by induction) that this extends to arbitrary finite sets of real numbers: |x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n}|\leq|x_{1}|+|x_{2}|+\cdots+|x_{n}|. Actually, with a bit more work one can show that the same claim holds for infinite sums, that is, series. That is, if a series \sum x_{n} converges absolutely, then \left|\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x_{n}ight|\leq\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}|x_{n}|. (Prove it!) Roughly speaking, we can think of an integral as being a kind of “continuously indexed infinite sum.” So it’s natural to ask whether a Triangle Inequality holds for integrals too. Theorem 12.18 (The Triangle Inequality for Riemann Integrals) If f:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is continuous, then \left|\int_{a}^{b}fight|\leq\int_{a}^{b}|f|. Proof. For all x\in[a,b] , -|f(x)|\leq f(x)\leq|f(x)| so, by Proposition 12.17, -\int_{a}^{b}|f|\leq\int_{a}^{b}f\leq\int_{a}^{b}|f|, whence the claim immediately follows. ∎ 12.5 The Fundamental Theorem of the Calculus So far we have developed some powerful theoretical tools to show that a given function is integrable and to relate the integrals of related integrable functions, but we don’t have any really convenient techniques for actually computing Riemann integrals. To compute \int_{0}^{1}x^{2}\,dx, for example, we had to resort to exhibiting a sequence of dissections whose upper and lower sums converge to a common limit, in this case,  rac{1}{3} (see Example 12.10). In principle, we can always compute Riemann integrals like this, but in practice this method of computing integrals is very onerous and, unless the integrand (the function to be integrated) is fairly simple, is likely to be intractable. Consider, for example, attempting to compute \int_{0}^{\pi}\sin x\,dx using this method. We know that this integral exists (Theorem 12.13) because we know that \sin is continuous, but we have no hope of computing it directly using Riemann sums. In this section, we establish a fundamental connexion between Riemann integration and differentiation which will give us a convenient means of computing \int_{a}^{b}f whenever we can dream up a function whose derivative equals f . Once we have done this we will rarely have to resort to computing sequences of Riemann sums to compute integrals. Theorem 12.19 (Fundamental Theorem of the Calculus version 1) Let I\subseteq{\mathbb{R}} be an interval, f:Iightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be continuous and a\in I . Define F:Iightarrow{\mathbb{R}} by F(x)=\int_{a}^{x}f. Then F is differentiable, and F^{\prime}=f . Proof. First note that F is well-defined (that is, the integral defining F(x) exists for all x\in I ) by Theorem 12.13 since f is continuous on [a,x]\subseteq I if x\geq a , and continuous on [x,a]\subseteq I if x<a . We wish to compute \lim_{yightarrow x} rac{F(y)-F(x)}{y-x}. So, let (y_{n}) be any sequence in I{ ackslash}\{x\} such that y_{n}ightarrow x , and s_{n}= rac{F(y_{n})-F(x)}{y_{n}-x}. We must show that s_{n}ightarrow f(x) . For each n , either y_{n}>x or y_{n}<x . If y_{n}>x then, by Theorem 12.14, s_{n}= rac{1}{y_{n}-x}\int_{x}^{y_{n}}f, whereas if y_{n}<x , s_{n}= rac{1}{x-y_{n}}\int_{y_{n}}^{x}f. In either case, by the Extreme Value Theorem, there exist w_{n} and z_{n} between x and y_{n} such that f(w_{n}) is the minimum value of f on the closed interval with endpoints x and y_{n} , and f(z_{n}) is the maximum value of f on this interval. Hence, by Proposition 12.17, \displaystyle rac{1}{y_{n}-x}f(w_{n})(y_{n}-x)\leq \displaystyle s_{n} \displaystyle\leq rac{1}{y_{n}-x}f(z_{n})(y_{n}-x)\qquad\mbox{if $y_{n}>x$,} \displaystyle\mbox{and}\qquad rac{1}{x-y_{n}}f(w_{n})(x-y_{n})\leq \displaystyle s_{n} \displaystyle\leq rac{1}{x-y_{n}}f(z_{n})(x-y_{n})\qquad\mbox{if $y_{n}<x$.} In either case, we conclude that f(w_{n})\leq s_{n}\leq f(z_{n}). Now, y_{n}ightarrow x so w_{n}ightarrow x and z_{n}ightarrow x also, by the Squeeze Rule, and f is continuous, so f(w_{n})ightarrow f(x) and f(z_{n})ightarrow f(x) . Hence, by the Squeeze Rule again, s_{n}ightarrow f(x) , which completes the proof. ∎ As a by-product of this theorem we see that any function which is continuous on an interval is the derivative of some differentiable function on that interval, an interesting and far from obvious fact. Even better, Theorem 12.19 immediately implies a second theorem which renders the job of computing many Riemann integrals almost trivial: Theorem 12.20 (Fundamental Theorem of the Calculus version 2) Let f:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be continuous and F:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be any differentiable function such that F^{\prime}=f . Then \int_{a}^{b}f=F(b)-F(a). Proof. Define the function g:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , g(x)=\left(\int_{a}^{x}fight)-F(x). Then, by Theorem 12.19 and the definition of F , g^{\prime}(x)=f(x)-f(x)=0 for all x\in[a,b] . Hence, by Proposition 10.9, g is constant, so g(b)=g(a) , that is \left(\int_{a}^{b}fight)-F(b)=\left(\int_{a}^{a}fight)-F(a)=0-F(a), and the result immediately follows. ∎ Example 12.21 Compute the Riemann integrals (i)​ \displaystyle{\int_{-1}^{1}x^{2}\,dx} , (ii)​ \displaystyle{\int_{0}^{\pi}\sin x\,dx} , Solution:  (i) Let f(x)=x^{2} and F(x)=x^{3}/3 . Then f is continuous and F^{\prime}=f on [-1,1] so, by Theorem 12.20, \int_{-1}^{1}f=F(1)-F(-1)= rac{2}{3}. (ii) Let f(x)=\sin x and F(x)=-\cos x . Then f is continuous and F^{\prime}=f on [0,\pi] so, by Theorem 12.20, \int_{0}^{\pi}f=F(\pi)-F(0)=-\cos\pi+\cos 0=2. \Box Exercise 12.22 Let f:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , f(x)=\int_{x}^{x^{2}+1} rac{t}{t^{2}+1}dt. Compute f^{\prime}(x) . Check your answer by watching this [VIDEO]. Having established Theorem 12.20, we see that we can explicitly compute \int_{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx if we can think of an antiderivative of f , that is, any function whose derivative is f(x) . This trick is so pervasive in integral calculus that it leads the unwary to identify integration of f (that is, the process of computing a Riemann integral \int_{a}^{b}f ) with the process of writing down an antiderivative of f . Indeed, it is common practice to call an antiderivative of f an indefinite integral of f and to denote any such function by the symbol \int f(x)\,dx. This notation has some practical advantages, but it also, unfortunately, generates a huge amount of confusion. Note that \int_{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx is a single number and that its definition has nothing whatsoever to do with antiderivatives of f : it is the unique real number which is no greater than any upper Riemann sum of f on [a,b] and no less than any lower Riemann sum of f on [a,b] . In particular, it is not a function of the “variable” x . Indeed, we could equally well have written it \int_{a}^{b}f(y)\,dy or \int_{a}^{b}f(\Gamma_{\widehat{\aleph}})\,d\Gamma_{\widehat{\aleph}} , which is one reason to prefer the simpler notation \int_{a}^{b}f . It is a function of a and b , however. By contrast, \int f(x)\,dx is just a (slightly ambiguous) symbol denoting any function whose derivative (at x ) is f(x) . It is a function of x , not a single number, and its definition has nothing to do with Riemann sums. That these two things turn out to be closely related is (as its name suggests) a very important theorem: the Fundamental Theorem of the Calculus. To understand calculus properly it is important to maintain a clear conceptual distinction between the Riemann integral \int_{a}^{b}f and any antiderivative that one might use to compute it. We have now rigorously developed all the fundamental concepts of differential and integral calculus. It would be a straightforward matter to combine the Fundamental Theorem of the Calculus with the Product Rule of differentiation to develop the technique of integration by parts, or with the Chain Rule to develop the technique of integration by substitution. Such development requires no new analytic insight and so is better placed in a course on the methods of calculus, rather than a course on real analysis such as this. Summary •​A dissection of [a,b] is a finite subset \mathscr{D}=\{a_{0},a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\} of [a,b] such that a=a_{0}<a_{1}<a_{2}<\cdots<a_{n}=b. •​Given a bounded function f:[a,b]ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , and a dissection \mathscr{D} , the lower Riemann sum is l_{\mathscr{D}}(f)=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\inf\{f(x)\>:\>a_{j-1}\leq x\leq a_{j}\}(a_{j% }-a_{j-1}), and the upper Riemann sum is u_{\mathscr{D}}(f)=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\sup\{f(x)\>:\>a_{j-1}\leq x\leq a_{j}\}(a_{j% }-a_{j-1}). •​ f is Riemann integrable if there exists a sequence (\mathscr{D}_{n}) of dissections of [a,b] such that u_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) and l_{\mathscr{D}_{n}}(f) converge to a common limit. In this case, we denote this limit by \int_{a}^{b}f and call it the Riemann integral of f (on, or over, [a,b] ). •​It follows from this definition that all continuous functions are Riemann integrable. •​We also proved \displaystyle\mbox{The { f Join Rule}:}\quad\int_{a}^{b}f+\int_{b}^{c}f=\int_% {a}^{c}f, \displaystyle\mbox{The { f Linearity Property}:}\quad\int_{a}^{b}(\alpha f+%  eta g)=\alpha\int_{a}^{b}f+ eta\int_{a}^{b}g where \alpha, eta are constants. •​There is an important link between Riemann integrals and derivatives, given by the Fundamental Theorem of the Calculus:  ullet ​Version 1: if f is continuous and F(x)=\int_{a}^{x}f , then F^{\prime}=f .  ullet ​Version 2: if f is continuous and F is some antiderivative of f (that is, a function satisfying F^{\prime}=f ), then \int_{a}^{b}f=F(b)-F(a) . •​Version 2 of the Fundamental Theorem of the Calculus provides a flexible and convenient method for computing many Riemann integrals. Previous page

Skip to content. toolbar 2 Sequences A real sequence is a mapping a:{\mathbb{Z}}^{+}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , that is, a rule which assigns to each positive integer n some real number a(n) . Actually, for sequences, unlike pretty much all other functions, it’s conventional to write the image of n under the mapping a as a_{n} instead of a(n) , and call it the { f n}^{\mbox{th}} term of the sequence, rather than the “image of n .” It’s also conventional to denote the mapping as (a_{n})_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+}} , or just (a_{n}) for short, rather than a:{\mathbb{Z}}^{+}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} . We will follow these conventions. Often we will specify a sequence just by giving a formula for its n^{\mbox{th}} term. Example 2.1 a_{n}= rac{n^{2}+5}{n^{2}} is a sequence whose first 4 terms are \displaystyle 6,\qquad rac{9}{4},\qquad rac{14}{9},\qquad rac{21}{16}. As n gets very large, a_{n} gets very close to 1 : for example a_{n}=1 to 3 decimal places for all n\geq 101 . So for n this large, we can approximate the sequence by the constant number 1 , provided we’re happy to accept errors no larger than 5	imes 10^{-4} . What if we’re a bit fussier than this, and need to know a_{n} to at least 5 decimal places? How big must n be before we can approximate a_{n} by the constant 1 ? We need \displaystyle 0.999995\leq a_{n}<1.000005\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad \displaystyle\Leftrightarrow \displaystyle 0.999995\leq 1+ rac{5}{n^{2}}<1.000005 \displaystyle\Leftrightarrow \displaystyle-0.000005\leq rac{5}{n^{2}}<0.000005 \displaystyle\Leftrightarrow \displaystyle rac{5}{n^{2}}<5	imes 10^{-6} \displaystyle\Leftrightarrow \displaystyle n^{2}>10^{6} \displaystyle\Leftrightarrow \displaystyle n>1000. So, for all n\geq 1001 , a_{n}=1 to 5 decimal places. In fact, however many decimal; places of accuracy we insist on, there is a point in the sequence beyond which, to that accuracy, a_{n} is just 1 . Example 2.2 Contrast this with a_{n}=\sin n , whose first 4 terms (to 5 decimal places) are 0.84147,\quad 0.90930,\quad 0.14112\quad\mbox{ and}-0.75680. The behaviour of this sequence as n grows large is not at all uniform; the terms bounce around seemingly at random with -1<a_{n}<1 . Sometimes it’s more convenient to define a sequence inductively. In its simplest form, this is when we specify the first term a_{1} , and give a rule for constructing a_{n+1} from a_{n} . Example 2.3 Let (a_{n}) be the sequence whose first term is a_{1}=1 , for which a_{n+1}= rac{a_{n}}{1+a_{n}^{2}}. The first 4 terms of this sequence are \displaystyle a_{1} \displaystyle= \displaystyle 1\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad \displaystyle a_{2} \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{1}{1+1^{2}}= rac{1}{2} \displaystyle a_{3} \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{1/2}{1+(1/4)}= rac{2}{5} \displaystyle a_{4} \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{2/5}{1+(4/25)}= rac{10}{29} What happens to a_{n} as n gets very large? This is actually quite hard to answer directly, even using a computer package such as Maple, because the terms become very unwieldy as n gets even moderately large. For example a_{8}= rac{268440386798659418988490}{1099331737522548368039021}, and Maple has trouble computing even a_{30} , because the integers involved get so large. We can convert each a_{n} to a truncated decimal expansion, using the command evalf, which greatly speeds up the calculation, but this gives rounding errors which accumulate as n increases, so by the time we get to a_{1000} , say,it’s not obvious whether the answer Maple produces ( 0.02234293705 , for what it’s worth) bears any relation to reality. Another interesting question is whether the large n behaviour of this sequence depends on our choice of initial term, a_{1}=1 . What if a_{1}=0 ? Or a_{1}=1000 ? We will develop methods which will allow us to show that, whatever a_{1} we choose, a_{n} for large n becomes very close to 0 – despite the fact that we have no idea how to write down a_{n} in general! 2.1 Convergence of sequences In Example 2.1, the terms of the sequence “tend to” 1 as n gets arbitrarily large, whereas in Example 2.2, the terms bounce around indefinitely, without tending to a particular value. We say that a_{n}=(n^{2}+5)/n^{2} converges to 1 , while a_{n}=\sin n does not converge. It is now time to make this concept of convergence precise. What does this have to do with convergence of sequences? In saying that a_{n}= rac{(n^{2}+5)}{n^{2}} converges to 1 , we are saying, roughly, that the terms a_{n} are close to 1 for large n . In terms of absolute values, this means that |a_{n}-1| is small for large n . More precisely, we make the following definition: Definition 2.4 A real sequence (a_{n}) converges to a real number L if, for each \varepsilon>0 there exists some positive integer N such that for all n\geq N , |a_{n}-L|<\varepsilon . In this case, we will write a_{n}ightarrow L . The number L is called the limit of the sequence (a_{n}) , and is often denoted \lim a_{n} or \lim_{nightarrow\infty}a_{n} . Remarks •​This is the most important definition in this course, and it is vitally important that you understand it thoroughly. It is the first rigorous definition of limit we have encountered. Other definitions of limit (e.g.  \lim_{xightarrow a}f(x) ) will be constructed from it. •​The definition says that given any \varepsilon>0 , no matter how small, there is a term in the sequence, a_{N} , after which all terms in the sequence lie within distance \varepsilon of L . •​Note that |a_{n}-L|<\varepsilon is equivalent to L-\varepsilon<a_{n}<L+\varepsilon . •​If we imagine plotting the terms of the sequence a_{n} on a graph (with n along the x axis and a_{n} along the y axis), we can construct a geometric picture of what the definition means. Given any positive number \varepsilon , construct the horizontal strip of height 2\varepsilon centred on the line y=L . Then there exists a point N on the x axis, to the right of which all points on the graph lie in the strip. [Uncaptioned image] This is true no matter how small we make \varepsilon . If we make \varepsilon smaller, the strip gets narrower, and the N beyond which all terms lie in the strip (probably) moves to the right. [Uncaptioned image] •​So N will, in general, depend on \varepsilon : if \varepsilon is large, a fairly small N will probably work, whereas if \varepsilon is very small, N will probably have to be very large. For our purposes the important thing is to establish that given any \varepsilon>0 there is a corresponding N which works for that particular \varepsilon . The relationship between \varepsilon and N is not important, nor is it important to know the smallest N which will work for a given \varepsilon . •​Note that, directly from the definition, a_{n}ightarrow L is and only if the sequence b_{n}=a_{n}-L satisfies b_{n}ightarrow 0 . If I ask you to prove from first principles that a given sequence (a_{n}) converges to a given limit L , I am asking you to show directly that, given any \varepsilon>0 , there is some N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that whenever n\geq N , |a_{n}-L|<\varepsilon . The key to doing this is to “estimate” (that is, rigorously find an upper bound on) the quantity |a_{n}-L| . Example 2.5 Claim: The sequence a_{n}= rac{1}{n}ightarrow 0 Proof. We suppose that we are given \epsilon>0 - to prove that a_{n}ightarrow 0 we need to find an N\in\mathbb{N} such that if n>N then |a_{n}-0|=|a_{n}|<\epsilon . As 1/\epsilon is a real number, by the Archimidean property of the reals, there is an integer N> rac{1}{\epsilon} . Then, for any n\geq N , |a_{n}|=\left| rac{1}{n}ight|= rac{1}{n}\leq rac{1}{N}< rac{1}{ rac{1}{% \epsilon}}=\epsilon where we repeatedly used that if a>b then  rac{1}{b}> rac{1}{a} . ∎ Example 2.6 Claim: a_{n}= rac{n^{2}+5}{n^{2}}ightarrow 1 . Proof. Let \varepsilon>0 be given. Then 5/\varepsilon is a real number, so by the Archimedean Property, there exists a positive integer N such that N> rac{5}{\varepsilon} . Now, for all n\geq N , \displaystyle|a_{n}-1| \displaystyle= \displaystyle\left| rac{n^{2}+5}{n^{2}}-1ight|=\left| rac{5}{n^{2}}ight|% = rac{5}{n^{2}}\leq rac{5}{n}\qquad\mbox{(since $n\geq 1$)} \displaystyle\leq \displaystyle rac{5}{N}<\varepsilon. Hence, given any \varepsilon>0 , there exists N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that |a_{n}-1|<\varepsilon for all n\geq N . Hence a_{n}ightarrow 1 . ∎ Note that Definition 2.4 does not say that a_{n} “gets closer and closer to L as n gets larger”, because this isn’t necessarily true. For example, the sequence (2.1) (2.1) a_{n}=\left\{ egin{array}[]{ll} rac{1}{n}&\mbox{$n$ odd}\ &\  rac{1}{n^{2}}&\mbox{$n$ even}\end{array}ight. does not have this property, because each odd term is further away from 0 than the previous even term. Nonetheless, (a_{n}) certainly converges to 0 . To prove this, we only need a minor variation of the argument used in Example 2.6 Example 2.7 Claim: the sequence defined in equation (2.1) converges to 0 . Proof. Let \varepsilon>0 be given. Then 1/\varepsilon is a real number, so by the Archimedean Property, there exists a positive integer N such that N> rac{1}{\varepsilon} . Now, for all n\geq N , \displaystyle|a_{n}-0| \displaystyle= \displaystyle a_{n}\qquad\mbox{(since $a_{n}>0$ for all $n$)}\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad \displaystyle= \displaystyle\left\{ egin{array}[]{ll} rac{1}{n}&\mbox{$n$ odd}\  rac{1}{n^{2}}&\mbox{$n$ even}\end{array}ight. \displaystyle\leq \displaystyle rac{1}{n}\qquad\mbox{(since $n\geq 1$)} \displaystyle\leq \displaystyle rac{1}{N} \displaystyle< \displaystyle\varepsilon. Hence, given any \varepsilon>0 , there exists N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that |a_{n}-0|<\varepsilon for all n\geq N . Hence a_{n}ightarrow 0 . ∎ Note that Definition 2.4 does not merely say that given any \varepsilon>0 there is some N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that |a_{N}-L|<\varepsilon . The definition certainly implies this, but is considerably stronger. For example, consider the sequence a_{n}=(-1)^{n} . Then given any \varepsilon>0 , there is an N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that |a_{n}-1|<\varepsilon . For example, N=2 will do for any \varepsilon>0 , since |a_{2}-1|=|1-1|=0<\varepsilon . But clearly a_{n} does not converge to 1 . In fact, a_{n} does not converge to anything. Can we prove this? Yes: Example 2.8 Claim: the sequence a_{n}=(-1)^{n} does not converge (to any limit). Proof. Assume, to the contrary, that a_{n}ightarrow L . Then, given any positive number \varepsilon , there exists N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that |a_{n}-L|<\varepsilon for all n\geq N . In particular, this must be true in the case \varepsilon= rac{1}{2} : there exists N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that, for all n\geq N , |a_{n}-L|< rac{1}{2} . But then N and N+1 are consecutive integers, so one is odd and the other is even, and hence |a_{N+1}-a_{N}|=2 . But, by the triangle inequality, |a_{N+1}-a_{N}|=|(a_{N+1}-L)-(a_{N}-L)|\leq|a_{N+1}-L|+|a_{N}-L|< rac{1}{2}+%  rac{1}{2}=1 by the definition of N . Hence 2<1 , a contradiction. ∎ We next establish that two rather simple, but important, sequences converge to their expected limits. Example 2.9 The constant sequence, a_{n}=c for all n , converges to c . Proof. Given any \varepsilon>0 we can take N=1 , since for all n\geq 1 , |a_{n}-c|=|c-c|=0<\varepsilon . ∎ Direct proofs of this kind are often called “ \varepsilon – N proofs”. We finish this section by showing how a direct \varepsilon – N proof can be made even for a reasonably complicated sequence. Example 2.10 Claim: \displaystyle{a_{n}= rac{n^{2}-\sin n}{(2n-7)(3n+1)}ightarrow rac{1}{6}}. Proof. The key is to estimate |a_{n}- rac{1}{6}| . For all n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} , \displaystyle\left|a_{n}- rac{1}{6}ight| \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{1}{6}\left| rac{6n^{2}-6\sin n-(2n-7)(3n+1)}{(2n-7)(3n+1)}ight| \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{1}{6} rac{|6n^{2}-6\sin n-(6n^{2}-19n-7)|}{|2n-7||3n+1|} \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{1}{6} rac{|19n-6\sin n+7|}{(2n-7)(3n+1)}\qquad\mbox{(if $n% \geq 4$)} \displaystyle\leq \dis