eq L_{2} . Let \displaystyle{\varepsilon= rac{1}{2}{|L_{1}-L_{2}|}>0} . Since a_{n}ightarrow L_{1} , there exists N_{1}\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that, for all n\geq N_{1} , |a_{n}-L_{1}|<\varepsilon. Similarly, since a_{n}ightarrow L_{2} , there exists N_{2}\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that, for all n\geq N_{2} , |a_{n}-L_{2}|<\varepsilon. Now let n be any positive integer greater than both N_{1} and N_{2} (for example n=N_{1}+N_{2} ). Then both the above inequalities hold, and so, \displaystyle 2\varepsilon=|L_{2}-L_{1}| \displaystyle= \displaystyle|(a_{n}-L_{1})-(a_{n}-L_{2})|\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad \displaystyle\leq \displaystyle|a_{n}-L_{1}|+|a_{n}-L_{2}|\qquad\mbox{(by the Triangle % Inequality)} \displaystyle< \displaystyle\varepsilon+\varepsilon\qquad\mbox{(since $n>N_{1}$ and $n>N_{2}$)} that is, 2\varepsilon<2\varepsilon , a contradiction. Hence, the original assumption (that (a_{n}) has two different limits) must be false. ∎ So we are justified in speaking of the limit of a convergent sequence. Definition 2.12 We say that a real sequence (a_{n}) is bounded above if its rangeis bounded above, that is, if there exists M\in{\mathbb{R}} such that for all n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} , a_{n}\leq M . Similarly, (a_{n}) is bounded below if there is a L\in\mathbb{R} such that for all n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+} , L\leq a_{n} . We will say that (a_{n}) is bounded if it is bounded both above and below. Proposition 2.13 If a sequence converges then it is bounded. Proof. Assume a_{n}ightarrow L . Then given any \varepsilon>0 , there exists N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that, for all n\geq N , |a_{n}-L|<\varepsilon . This is true, in particular, in the case \varepsilon=1 . Hence, there exists N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that, for all n\geq N , |a_{n}-L|<1 . Let K=\max\{|a_{1}-L|,|a_{2}-L|,\ldots,|a_{N-1}-L|,1\}, which exists since the set is finite. Then for all n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} , |a_{n}-L|\leq K , and hence, L-K\leq a_{n}\leq L+K . Hence, the sequence (a_{n}) is bounded (above by L+K and below by L-K ). ∎ Of course, the converse of this Proposition is false: not every bounded sequence is convergent, as we have already seen (for example a_{n}=(-1)^{n} is bounded, but not convergent). If a sequence is convergent, it’s bounded above and below, and it’s not hard to show that its limit must lie between the upper and lower bounds: Proposition 2.14 If K\leq a_{n}\leq M for all n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} and (a_{n}) converges to L , then K\leq L\leq M . Proof. Exercise. The obvious strategy is a proof by contradiction. That is, assume a_{n}ightarrow L but L
