Skip to content. toolbar 9 Differentiable functions 9.1 The main definition OK, let’s build calculus. Now that we have a rigorous definition of the limit of a function, it is straightforward to define derivatives. Definition 9.1 Let f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , where D is some subset of {\mathbb{R}} , and a\in D be a cluster point of D . Then f is differentiable at a if the limit \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a} exists. In this case, we denote the limit f^{\prime}(a) and call it the derivative of f at a . We say that f is differentiable if it is differentiable at a for all a\in D . Remarks •​In general, in order to define \lim_{xightarrow a}g(x) , we only need a to be a cluster point of the domain of g : it isn’t necessary in general for a to be in the domain of g , so g(a) may or may not exist. For example \lim_{xightarrow 1} rac{x^{2}-1}{x-1} exists, although the function is undefined at x=1 . Note, however, that the limit defining f^{\prime}(a) contains the number f(a) , so to be differentiable at a , the point a must be both an element and a cluster point of the domain of f . For example, a function f:(0,\infty)ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} cannot be differentiable at 0 (since 0
otin(0,\infty) ), and a function f:{\mathbb{Z}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} cannot be differentiable anywhere (since {\mathbb{Z}} has no cluster points). •​The limit in Definition 9.1 is defined as in Definition 7.1. That is, f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is differentiable at a if for all sequences (x_{n}) in D{ ackslash}\{a\} which converge to a ,  rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a}ightarrow f^{\prime}(a). •​Geometrically, the quantity s_{n}= rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a} is the slope of the straight line passing through the points (a,f(a)) and (x_{n},f(x_{n})) . Such a straight line is called a chord on the graph y=f(x) . As x_{n} approaches a , the points defining the chord get “arbitrarily close” to one another, and the chords approach a straight line through (a,f(a)) with slope f^{\prime}(a) , the so-called tangent line. This is why the derivative f^{\prime}(a) is often interpreted as the slope of the graph y=f(x) at the point (a,f(a)) . Note, however, that this is just an interpretation. The definition of f^{\prime}(a) is in terms of limits which are, in turn, defined precisely in Definition 7.1. [Uncaptioned image] •​If f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is differentiable, then its derivative is also a function f^{\prime}:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , mapping D to {\mathbb{R}} . There is a very popular alternative notation for the derivative in this case, namely f^{\prime}(x)= rac{df}{dx}. This notation is convenient in some circumstances, but it tends to blur the distinction between a function (in this case f^{\prime} ) and the value of the function at a particular point (in this case f^{\prime}(x) ), so we will tend to avoid it. Let’s verify that some simple, familiar functions have the derivatives we expect. Example 9.2 Let f:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} such that f(x)=c , a constant. Then f is differentiable (everywhere) and f^{\prime}(a)=0 for all a\in{\mathbb{R}} . Proof. Choose any a\in{\mathbb{R}} and let x_{n} be any sequence in {\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{a\} which converges to a . Then  rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a}= rac{c-c}{x_{n}-a}=0ightarrow 0. Hence \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}=0 as was to be proved. ∎ Example 9.3 Let f:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} such that f(x)=x . Then f is differentiable (everywhere) and f^{\prime}(a)=1 for all a\in{\mathbb{R}} . Proof. Choose any a\in{\mathbb{R}} and let x_{n} be any sequence in {\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{a\} which converges to a . Then  rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a}= rac{x_{n}-a}{x_{n}-a}=1ightarrow 1. Hence \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}=1 as was to be proved. ∎ Example 9.4 Let f:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} such that f(x)=x^{2} . Then f is differentiable and f^{\prime}(a)=2a for all a\in{\mathbb{R}} . Proof. Choose any a\in{\mathbb{R}} and let x_{n} be any sequence in {\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{a\} which converges to a . Then  rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a}= rac{x_{n}^{2}-a^{2}}{x_{n}-a}= rac{(x_{n}-a)(% x_{n}+a)}{x_{n}-a}={x_{n}+a}ightarrow a+a. Hence \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}=2a as was to be proved. ∎ Example 9.5 Let f:{\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{0\}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} such that f(x)=1/x . Then f is differentiable and f^{\prime}(a)=-1/a^{2} for all a\in{\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{0\} . Proof. Choose any a
eq 0 and let x_{n} be any sequence in {\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{0,a\} which converges to a . Then \displaystyle rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a} \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{1/x_{n}-1/a}{x_{n}-a}= rac{a-x_{n}}{x_{n}a(x_{n}-a)}=-%  rac{1}{x_{n}a}ightarrow- rac{1}{a^{2}} by the Algebra of Limits (Theorem 2.15). Hence \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}=- rac{1}{a^{2}} as was to be proved. ∎ OK, all is as we expected. What about functions which are not differentiable? How do we prove they aren’t? A function f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is not differentiable at a precisely if the limit \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a} does not exist. To establish this. it suffices to find one example of a sequence (x_{n}) in D{ ackslash}\{a\} which converges to a for which  rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a} does not converge. Example 9.6 Let f:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} such that f(x)=|x| . Then f is not differentiable at 0 . Proof. Assume, towards a contradiction, that f is differentiable at 0 with derivative f^{\prime}(0) . Then \lim_{xightarrow 0} rac{f(x)-f(0)}{x-0}=f^{\prime}(0). Let x_{n}=(-1)^{n}/n . Note that this is a sequence in {\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{0\} converging to 0 . Hence,  rac{f(x_{n})-f(0)}{x_{n}-0}ightarrow f^{\prime}(0). But  rac{f(x_{n})-f(0)}{x_{n}-0}= rac{|(-1)^{n}/n|}{(-1)^{n}/n}= rac{1}{(-1)^{n% }}=(-1)^{n} which does not converge, a contradiction. Hence f is not differentiable at 0 . ∎ Remark Alternatively, we could have defined y_{n}=1/n and z_{n}=-1/n and noted that both are sequences in {\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{0\} converging to 0 , so if f is differentiable at 0 , then both  rac{f(y_{n})-f(0)}{y_{n}-0}\quad\mbox{and}\quad rac{f(z_{n})-f(0)}{z_{n}-0} must converge to f^{\prime}(0) . But the first converges to 1 , while the second converges to -1 , which contradicts the uniqueness of limits (Theorem 7.5). Exercise 9.7 Prove that f:[0,\infty)ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , f(x)=\sqrt{x} is not differentiable at 0 . If you get stuck, it may help to watch this [VIDEO] There is a link between differentiablity and continuity, as we now show. Proposition 9.8 Let f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be differentiable at a\in D . Then f is continuous at a . Proof. Let (x_{n}) be any sequence in D which converges to a . Choose any sequence (y_{n}) in D{ ackslash}\{a\} which converges to a (such a sequence must exist since a is a cluster point of D ) and let z_{n}:=\left\{ egin{array}[]{cc}x_{n}&\mbox{if $x_{n}
eq a$}\ y_{n}&\mbox{if $x_{n}=a$.}\end{array}ight. I leave it as an exercise to prove that z_{n}ightarrow a . Now |f(x_{n})-f(a)|=\left\{ egin{array}[]{cc}\left| rac{f(z_{n})-f(a)}{z_{n}-a}% ight||z_{n}-a|&\mbox{if $x_{n}
eq a$}\ 0&\mbox{if $x_{n}=a$}\end{array}ight\}\leq\left| rac{f(z_{n})-f(a)}{z_{n}-a% }ight||z_{n}-a|. Since f is differentiable at a and z_{n}ightarrow a ,  rac{f(z_{n})-f(a)}{z_{n}-a}ightarrow f^{\prime}(a). Hence, by the Algebra of Limits, \left| rac{f(z_{n})-f(a)}{z_{n}-a}ight||z_{n}-a|ightarrow|f^{\prime}(a)|% 	imes 0=0, so, by the Squeeze Rule |f(x_{n})-f(a)|ightarrow 0 , that is, f(x_{n})ightarrow f(a) . Since this holds for all such sequences (x_{n}) , f is continuous at a . ∎ Remark. The converse of Proposition 9.8 is false: if f is continuous at a , it does not follow that f is differentiable there. We’ve already seen a counterexample: f(x)=|x| is continuous at 0 but is not differentiable at 0 (see Example 9.6). In this case, the function fails to be differentiable only at a single isolated point. It is straightforward to construct functions which are differentiable only at a single isolated point. Example 9.9 Let f:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be defined such that f(x)=\left\{ egin{array}[]{ll}x&\mbox{if $x\in{\mathbb{Q}}$,}\ x-x^{2}&\mbox{if $x
otin{\mathbb{Q}}$.}\end{array}ight. I claim that f is differentiable at 0 , with f^{\prime}(0)=1 , but is not differentiable anywhere else. [Uncaptioned image] Proof. Let a\in{\mathbb{R}} and assume that f is differentiable at a . Then, by Proposition 9.8, f is continuous at a . For each n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} there exist r_{n}\in{\mathbb{Q}} and i_{n}\in{\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}{\mathbb{Q}} such that a<r_{n}<a+1/n and a<i_{n}<a+1/n . Clearly r_{n}ightarrow a and i_{n}ightarrow a by the Squeeze Rule. Hence, by the definition of continuity, f(r_{n})ightarrow f(a) and f(i_{n})ightarrow f(a) . But r_{n} is rational, so f(r_{n})=r_{n}ightarrow a , and i_{n} is irrational, so f(i_{n})=i_{n}-i_{n}^{2}ightarrow a-a^{2} . Both these limits equal f(a) , so a=a-a^{2} , whence a=0 . So if f is differentiable at a , then a=0 . Equivalently, f is not differentiable at any a
eq 0 . It remains to show that f is differentiable at 0 with f^{\prime}(0)=1 , that is, \lim_{xightarrow 0} rac{f(x)-f(0)}{x-0}=1. So, let (x_{n}) be any sequence in {\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{0\} converging to 0 , and consider s_{n}= rac{f(x_{n})-f(0)}{x_{n}-0}= rac{f(x_{n})}{x_{n}}. We must show that s_{n}ightarrow 1 . If x_{n} is rational, then |s_{n}-1|=|x_{n}/x_{n}-1|=0 , whereas if x_{n} is irrational then |s_{n}-1|=\left| rac{x_{n}-x_{n}^{2}}{x_{n}}-1ight|=|x_{n}|. Hence, for all n , 0\leq|s_{n}-1|\leq|x_{n}| , so |s_{n}-1|ightarrow 0 by the Squeeze Rule. Hence s_{n}ightarrow 1 . It follows that f^{\prime}(0)=1 , as claimed. ∎ So this (admittedly rather bizarre) function is differentiable at 0 , and has a positive derivative there. Naive intuition would suggest, therefore, that the function should be increasing, at least for values of x sufficiently close to 0 . In fact, this is false! Example 9.9 continued Claim: the function f is not increasing on any neighbourhood of 0 . That is, there does not exist \varepsilon>0 such that f is increasing on (-\varepsilon,\varepsilon) . Proof. Let \varepsilon>0 be given. Then there exists an irrational number x such that 0<x<\varepsilon . By definition, f(x)=x-x^{2}<x . Similarly, there exists a rational number y such that x-x^{2}<y<x . But then y<x and f(y)=y>x-x^{2}=f(x) . Hence, f is not increasing on the interval (-\varepsilon,\varepsilon) . This is true no matter which positive number \varepsilon we choose, which establishes the claim. ∎ 9.2 The rules of differentiation In principle, if we are given an explicit function, like f:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}},\qquad f(x)=(x^{3}+1)^{2}, we can show it is differentiable and compute its derivative by directly applying Definition 9.1. This quickly becomes complicated and tedious, however. So we next develop some “derivative theorems” which will allow us to reduce differentiation of many functions to an algorithmic process. You are (I would hope) already familiar with these and quite fluent in applying them. The point of this section is to show that, now we have a mathematically precise definition of the derivative, we can rigorously prove them, thus putting differential calculus on a solid foundation. Proposition 9.10 (Linearity) Let f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , g:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be differentiable at a\in D with derivatives f^{\prime}(a) and g^{\prime}(a) , respectively, and c be a real constant. Then (i)​ cf:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is differentiable at a with derivative cf^{\prime}(a) . (ii)​ f+g:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is differentiable at a with derivative f^{\prime}(a)+g^{\prime}(a) . Proof. These both follow immediately from the Algebra of Limits for functions (Theorem 7.10): \displaystyle\lim_{xightarrow a} rac{cf(x)-cf(a)}{x-a} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\lim_{xightarrow a}c\left( rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}ight)=cf^{% \prime}(a) \displaystyle\lim_{xightarrow a} rac{f(x)+g(x)-(f(a)+g(a))}{x-a} \displaystyle= \displaystyle\lim_{xightarrow a}\left( rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}+ rac{g(x)-g(a)}% {x-a}ight)=f^{\prime}(a)+g^{\prime}(a) ∎ Combining parts (i) and (ii) of Proposition 9.10, we see that linear combinations of differentiable functions are differentiable: for f,g differentiable at a and any constants \alpha, eta , h(x)=\alpha f(x)+ eta g(x) is differentiable at a , with derivative h^{\prime}(a)=\alpha f^{\prime}(a)+ eta g^{\prime}(a). What about products of differentiable functions? If f and g are differentiable at a , is h(x)=f(x)g(x) differentiable at a ? And if so, is h^{\prime}(a)=f^{\prime}(a)g^{\prime}(a) ? Yes (to the first) and no (to the second): Proposition 9.11 (Product Rule) Let f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , g:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be differentiable at a\in D with derivatives f^{\prime}(a) and g^{\prime}(a) , respectively. Then fg:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is differentiable at a with derivative f^{\prime}(a)g(a)+f(a)g^{\prime}(a) . Proof. Let h:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , h(x)=f(x)g(x) . We must show that \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{h(x)-h(a)}{x-a}=f^{\prime}(a)g(a)+f(a)g^{\prime}(a). So, let (x_{n}) be any sequence in D{ ackslash}\{a\} converging to a . Then \displaystyle rac{h(x_{n})-h(a)}{x_{n}-a} \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{f(x_{n})g(x_{n})-f(a)g(a)}{x_{n}-a} \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{f(x_{n})g(x_{n})-f(a)g(x_{n})+f(a)g(x_{n})-f(a)g(a)}{x_{n}-a} \displaystyle= \displaystyle rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a}g(x_{n})+f(a) rac{g(x_{n})-f(a)g(a)% }{x_{n}-a}. Now f is differentiable at a , so  rac{f(x_{n})-f(a)}{x_{n}-a}ightarrow f^{\prime}(a). Similarly, g is differentiable at a , so  rac{g(x_{n})-g(a)}{x_{n}-a}ightarrow g^{\prime}(a). Furthermore, since g is differentiable at a , it is continuous at a , so g(x_{n})ightarrow g(a). Hence, by the Algebra of Limits (for sequences, Theorem 2.15),  rac{h(x_{n})-h(a)}{x_{n}-a}ightarrow f^{\prime}(a)	imes g(a)+f(a)	imes g% ^{\prime}(a). Since this holds for all such sequences (x_{n}) , the claim is proved. ∎ Having established the Linearity Property and the Product Rule, it’s not hard to prove that all polynomial functions are differentiable, with the derivative we expect. Proposition 9.12 Every polynomial function p:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , p(x)=a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{m}x^{m} is differentiable, and its derivative is another polynomial function p^{\prime}:{\mathbb{R}}ightarrow{\mathbb{R}} , namely p^{\prime}(x)=a_{1}+2a_{2}x+\cdots+ma_{m}x^{m-1}. Proof. Exercise. Try proof by induction (on the degree of p ). If you get stuck, watch this [VIDEO] ∎ Propositions 9.10 and 9.11 followed easily from the Algebra of Limits. Our next differentiation rule, and its proof, are considerably more subtle. Recall that the composition of two functions f:Aightarrow B and g:Bightarrow C , denoted g\circ f:Aightarrow C is the function which first “does” f , then feeds the result into g , that is (g\circ f)(x)=g(f(x)). This only makes sense if the range of f is a subset of the domain of g . We’ve already proved that the composition of two continuous functions is continuous (Theorem 8.5). There’s a very famous rule which tells us that the composition of two differentiable functions is differentiable, and gives a formula for its derivative. Theorem 9.13 (Chain Rule) Let f:Dightarrow E be differentiable at a\in D and g:Eightarrow{\mathbb{R}} be differentiable at f(a)\in E . Then g\circ f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is differentiable at a , and (g\circ f)^{\prime}(a)=g^{\prime}(f(a))f^{\prime}(a). Proof. We consider two cases separately: (i) f^{\prime}(a)
eq 0 and (ii) f^{\prime}(a)=0 . (i) Let (x_{n}) be any sequence in D{ ackslash}\{a\} which converges to a and consider the sequence s_{n}= rac{(g\circ f)(x_{n})-(g\circ f)(a)}{x_{n}-a}. We must show that s_{n}ightarrow g^{\prime}(f(a))f^{\prime}(a) . I claim there must exist N\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} such that, for all n\geq N , f(x_{n})
eq f(a) . (More informally, there is a point in the sequence f(x_{n}) after which it never takes the value f(a) .) For if not, there is a subsequence (x_{n_{k}}) with f(x_{n_{k}})=f(a) for all k , which would imply that  rac{f(x_{n_{k}})-f(a)}{x_{n_{k}}-a}=0ightarrow 0. But x_{n_{k}}ightarrow a so the above sequence must converge to f^{\prime}(a) which is not 0, a contradiction. Now, consider the tail of the sequence (s_{n}) starting at its (N+1)^{\mbox{th}} term, that is, the subsequence (s_{N+n}) . Recall that, by the Tail Lemma (Lemma 4.5), if (s_{N+n}) converges, then (s_{n}) converges to the same limit. So it suffices to show that s_{N+n}ightarrow g^{\prime}(f(a))f^{\prime}(a) . But s_{N+n}= rac{g(f(x_{n+N}))-g(f(a))}{f(x_{n+N})-f(a)} rac{f(x_{n+N})-f(a)}{x_% {n+N}-a}, where we have used the fact that for all n\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{+} , f(x_{N+n})
eq f(a) . Since f is differentiable at a ,  rac{f(x_{n+N})-f(a)}{x_{n+N}-a}ightarrow f^{\prime}(a), and f is continuous at a (Proposition 9.8), so f(x_{n+N})ightarrow f(a) . But g is differentiable at f(a) , so for all sequences (y_{n}) in E{ ackslash}\{f(a)\} which converge to f(a) ,  rac{g(y_{n})-g(f(a))}{y_{n}-f(a)}ightarrow g^{\prime}(f(a)). Using this fact in the case y_{n}=f(x_{N+n}) , we see that  rac{g(f(x_{n+N}))-g(f(a))}{f(x_{n+N})-f(a)} rac{f(x_{n+N})-f(a)}{x_{n+N}-a}% ightarrow g^{\prime}(f(a)). Hence s_{N+n}ightarrow g^{\prime}(f(a))f^{\prime}(a) by the Algebra of Limits. (ii) Assume f^{\prime}(0)=0 . Further, assume towards a contradiction that \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{(g\circ f)(x)-(g\circ f)(a)}{x-a}
eq 0. Then there exists a sequence (x_{n}) in D{ ackslash}\{a\} which converges to a such that s_{n}= rac{(g\circ f)(x_{n})-(g\circ f)(a)}{x_{n}-a}
rightarrow 0. But recall (Example 6.13) this implies there exists a constant \varepsilon>0 and a subsequence (x_{n_{k}}) such that |s_{n_{k}}|\geq\varepsilon for all k . Clearly, for all k , f(x_{n_{k}})
