e}(x) \displaystyle= \displaystyle- rac{1}{x^{2}} \displaystyle h^{\prime}(x) \displaystyle= \displaystyle mx^{m-1}. Hence, by the Chain Rule, f is diffentiable, and \displaystyle f^{\prime}(x) \displaystyle= \displaystyle g^{\prime}(h(x))h^{\prime}(x)=- rac{1}{h(x)^{2}}mx^{m-1} \displaystyle= \displaystyle- rac{mx^{m-1}}{x^{2m}} \displaystyle= \displaystyle- rac{m}{x^{m+1}} by Example 9.5 and Proposition 9.12. ∎ Generalizing the trick used in this proof, we can obtain another useful rule of differentiation: Proposition 9.17 (Quotient Rule) Let f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} and g:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}}{ ackslash}\{0\} , be differentiable at a\in D . Then f/g is differentiable at a and \left( rac{f}{g}ight)^{\prime}(a)= rac{f^{\prime}(a)g(a)-f(a)g^{\prime}(a)% }{g(a)^{2}}. Proof. Exercise. If you get stuck, watch this [VIDEO] ∎ So we now know that the function f(x)=x^{k} is differentiable for all integers k (everywhere it is well-defined, i.e. everywhere except 0 if k<0 ), and that its derivative is f^{\prime}(x)=kx^{k-1} . Remark You are probably more familiar with the Chain Rule expressed something like the following: \qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad rac{dy}{dx}= rac{dy}{du} rac{du}{dx}.\qquad\qquad% \qquad\qquad(*) Certainly, this has a look of plausibility about it (don’t the “ du ’s” just cancel?) and is arguably more memorable than \qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad(g\circ f)^{\prime}(a)=g^{\prime}(f(a))f^{\prime}(a).% \qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad(\dagger) Nonetheless, it is vastly inferior. Ask yourself what, exactly, does (*) mean? The derivative of a function y (where? At x ?) equals the derivative (where? At u ?) of the same (?) function – but with respect to a different variable, whatever that means — times the derivative of some other function u (but isn’t u a variable? Can we use the same symbol to denote both a function and a variable?) evaluated somewhere ( x ? Maybe?). Note that “the function y thought of as a function of u instead of x ,” where “ u is a function of x ,” is actually a different function! And to interpret (*) we’re forced to talk about how we think about the function y , instead of what it actually is. This is the hallmark of imprecise, badly formulated mathematics. By contrast (\dagger) is a completely unambiguous, precise statement standing on its own. We don’t need to explain separately “how we’re thinking of” the terms it contains in order to make sense of it. Be warned: if ever I ask for a statement of the Chain Rule, it is Theorem 9.13 I want, not wooly, ambiguous stuff in the style of (*) . \Box Summary •​A function f:Dightarrow{\mathbb{R}} is differentiable at a\in D if \lim_{xightarrow a} rac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a} exists. In this case, we denote the limit f^{\prime}(a) and call it the derivative of f at a . We say that f is differentiable if it is differentiable at a for all a\in D . •​The limit in f^{\prime}(a) is defined as in Definition 7.1. •​If a function is differentiable at a , it is continuous at a . The converse is false. •​Using this definition of f^{\prime}(a) , we can prove that derivatives obey the usual rules of differential calculus, to wit:  egin{array}[]{lrcl}\vspace*{0.1cm}\mbox{Linearity:}&(\alpha f+ eta g)^{% \prime}(a)&=&\alpha f^{\prime}(a)+ eta g^{\prime}(a),\ \vspace*{0.1cm}\mbox{Product Rule:}&(fg)^{\prime}(a)&=&f^{\prime}(a)g(a)+f(a)g% ^{\prime}(a),\ \vspace*{0.1cm}\mbox{Quotient Rule:}&(f/g)^{\prime}(a)&=&\displaystyle{ rac{f% ^{\prime}(a)g(a)-f(a)g^{\prime}(a)}{g(a)^{2}}},\ \vspace*{0.1cm}\mbox{Chain Rule:}&(g\circ f)^{\prime}(a)&=&g^{\prime}(f(a))f^{% \prime}(a).\end{array} Previous page Next page
